<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900417-0006</DOCNO><DOCID>900417-0006.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- AmVestors Financial Corp.:   Junk Bond Woes Result   In Loss for Fourth Quarter</HL><DATE>04/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AVFC</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   AmVestors Financial Corp. said it had a net loss of $7.9million, or 55 cents a share, for the fourth quarter endedDec. 31, largely because of losses related to junk bonds.   In the fourth quarter of 1988, the Topeka, Kan.-based lifeinsurance concern had net income of about $2 million, or 15cents a share.</LP><TEXT>   AmVestors said its fourth-quarter results include $16.3million in investment losses, most of which were related tohigh-yield bonds issued by real-estate concerns. In thefourth quarter of 1988, it had investment losses of $930,158.   The company said it stopped purchasing high-yield bonds atyear end, and is now trying to reduce its junk-bond holdingsto less than 20% of assets by the end of 1990, from about 30%of assets at Dec. 31.   The fourth quarter also included a $6.1 million after-taxgain related to a co-insurance agreement in which AmVestorsceded 90% of the risk of its single-premium, whole-lifepolicies written before 1989.   For the year, AmVestors had a net loss of $4.5 million, or31 cents a share, after investment losses of $18.7 million.In 1988, AmVestors had net income of $6.6 million, or 58cents a share, after investment losses of $579,428.</TEXT></DOC>